tjacquin:
Hey guys, I'm having the exact same issue here. No solution yet?
EDIT:
I downloaded the first example of the playground and compared it with the version created on Cordova.
The thing I noticed is that the BOM are represented as \FE\FF (UTF-16) through the Chrome download and þÿ (ISO-8859-1) through Cordova.
Does anyone know if there is anything to do about it?
. So I looked into the issue a bit more and managed to resolve the problem.
I figured that the encoding was the cause of the problem.
At first, I was using the function getBase64 and calling atob() on the callback result which ended up creating a pdf but the encoding of the font was wrong.
Then I used getBuffer(),  converted the buffer to Uint8Array and converted the array to a binary array.
Writing this binary array to the persistent file in Cordova produced a readable PDF.
Here's the code I'm using (I'm using angular):
``` javascript
var binaryArray = null;
var currentfileEntry = null;
$scope.docDefinition = {"Put your scope definition here"};
function fail(error) {
    console.log(error.code);
};
function gotFS(fileSystem) {
    var fileName = "your-file.pdf";
    fileSystem.root.getFile(fileName, {
      create: true,
      exclusive: false
    }, gotFileEntry, fail);
}
function gotFileEntry(fileEntry) {
    currentfileEntry = fileEntry;
    fileEntry.createWriter(gotFileWriter, fail);
}
function gotFileWriter(writer) {
    writer.onwrite = function (evt) {
      $scope.downloading = false;
      alert("The file was written successfully");
      window.requestFileSystem(LocalFileSystem.PERSISTENT, 0, gotFSforRead, fail);
    }
    writer.write(binaryArray);
}
$scope.download = function () {
    if (!window.cordova) {
      pdfMake.createPdf($scope.docDefinition).open();
    } else {
      pdfMake.createPdf($scope.docDefinition).getBuffer(function (buffer) {
        var utf8 = new Uint8Array(buffer); // Convert to UTF-8...              
        binaryArray = utf8.buffer; // Convert to Binary...
        window.requestFileSystem(LocalFileSystem.PERSISTENT, 0, gotFS, fail);
      });
    }
}
```
I hope this will be helpful to other developers facing the same issue.
. As you can see in the $scope.download function, the behavior is different whether you are using this code within a browser or a Cordova app.
In a browser, the open() function will pop a base64 encoded PDF in a new tab. You don't need to add any dependency.
In a Cordova app, you need to write the PDF to the file system. As of Cordova 3.0, you need to include the file plugin:
cordova plugin add org.apache.cordova.file
Here's the reference on how to use the file API: http://docs.phonegap.com/en/edge/cordova_file_file.md.html
Hope that helps,
Thomas
