. One I had the base64 string, I added it as an attachment to my email.  The decoding was handled by the receiving email client.  The base64 encoding is just a way to send a binary document over the internet via http and othe protocols.  If you are doing everything local, you can save the file without encoding and open in a pdf reader.
. Can you post some of your code?  Otherwise you need to compare what you are putting  into the database with what is coming out.  It is possible that the round trip through the database is encoding a second time, decoding it, or something else.
.%PDF-1.3  .... looks like a valid decode.  So your issue has to be with the writing of the file.
So in my world I do everything in the client.  Create the PDF convert to base64, do an http POST to my PHP server and then send the file as an attachment.
I'm assuming that you are doing everything in the client so you need to to use the Blob.js and a file system library of some sort.  Check out https://www.npmjs.com/package/angular-file-saver.
Check out this fiddle as well http://jsfiddle.net/onury/5gWFL/   The only difference is that you'd set the type like
var file = new Blob([MyDecodedPDF], {type: 'application/pdf'});
 var fileURL = URL.createObjectURL(file);
