jbjorge:
@jafar-rezaei To mitigate the issue when I first stumbled upon it I switched away from using percent when defining widths. Since the pdf is scaled after a physical format, the sizes for the page is known from standardPageSizes.js.
The size of the table padding and vertical lines are known through
javascript
{
  table: { ... },
  layout: {
    paddingLeft: function(i, node) { return 4; },
    paddingRight: function(i, node) { return 4; },
    hLineWidth: function (i, node) { return 1; },
    vLineWidth: function (i, node) { return 1; },
  }
}
and the size of the page margins are known through
javascript
const docDefinition = {
    pageSize: [595.28, 841.89],
    pageMargins: [ 10, 10 ]
}
Things in pdfmake may have been changed since I implemented it in our codebase, but if I remember correctly i had to account for those things when calculating 25% width out of a page that is e.g. A4.
I might have forgotten some things to take into account when calculating, but I guess this is a starting point to get you going in the playground.. To know more about the error you're getting, try to reproduce it with as small document definition as you can make and post it here.
Regarding pagesize, the predefined items actually translate to a width/height within the library. This means that you can define the width/height yourself if you want.
javascript
var dd = {
    pageSize: {width: 500, height: 400},
    content: ['hello there']
}
